:::summary
Thomas Aquinas (1225–1274) was a Dominican friar, philosopher, and theologian whose *Summa Theologica* represents the greatest synthesis of Christian faith and Aristotelian philosophy ever attempted. His Five Ways — arguments for the existence of God — remain some of the most discussed proofs in the history of philosophy. Though his metaphysical assumptions differ from Latter-day Saint theology, his commitment to rigorous reason in service of faith is admirable.
:::

